Practical 2: Implement Word Count Using MapReduce

Aim: Implement a Word Count program using Hadoop MapReduce.

Prerequisites
Hadoop installed and configured (Practical 1)
Hadoop services running
Step 1: Start Hadoop

Open Command Prompt as Administrator

cd C:\Hadoop\sbin

Run:

start-dfs.cmd
start-yarn.cmd

Check services:

jps

You should see:

NameNode
DataNode
ResourceManager
NodeManager
Jps
Step 2: Turn Off Safe Mode (if enabled)
hdfs dfsadmin -safemode leave

Expected Output:

Safe mode is OFF
Step 3: Create Input Directory in HDFS
hdfs dfs -mkdir /input_dir

Verify:

hdfs dfs -ls /
Step 4: Create Input File

Create a file:

C:\input_file.txt

Write the following content:

Hadoop is Big Data Framework
Hadoop is Open Source
Big Data is Future

Save the file.

Step 5: Upload File to HDFS
hdfs dfs -put C:\input_file.txt /input_dir

Verify:

hdfs dfs -ls /input_dir

Expected Output:

Found 1 items
/input_dir/input_file.txt
Step 6: View File Contents
hdfs dfs -cat /input_dir/input_file.txt

Output:

Hadoop is Big Data Framework
Hadoop is Open Source
Big Data is Future
Step 7: Run MapReduce Word Count
hadoop jar C:\Hadoop\share\hadoop\mapreduce\hadoop-mapreduce-examples-3.3.0.jar wordcount /input_dir /output_dir

Note: If /output_dir already exists, delete it first:

hdfs dfs -rm -r /output_dir

Then run the command again.

Step 8: Verify Output Directory
hdfs dfs -ls /output_dir

Expected Output:

part-r-00000
_SUCCESS
Step 9: Display Output
hdfs dfs -cat /output_dir/part-r-00000
